# Commit messages

All commit messages must be written in **English** (subject and body).

Clear messages help future readers see **what** changed and **why**, make selective
reverts easier, and support release notes. Avoid vague subjects like “Tweaked a
few things”.

## Conventional Commits (recommended)

Use this shape when it fits the change:

```
<type>[optional scope]: <Description>

[optional body]

[optional footer(s)]
```

- **type** (pick one): `feat`, `fix`, `refactor`, `chore`, `perf`, `ci`, `ops`,
  `build`, `docs`, `style`, `revert`, `test`
- **scope** (optional): area of the codebase, e.g. `feat(api): Add rate limit`
- **Description**: short imperative summary after the colon; **capitalize** the
  first word of the description (e.g. `feat: Add unit tests for user auth`).

Common types: `feat` (new feature), `fix` (bug fix), `refactor` (restructure
without fixing or adding behavior), `chore` (deps, tooling, misc), `perf`
(performance), `ci` (CI config), `ops` (infra, deploy, backup, recovery),
`build` (build system, pipeline, version bumps), `docs` (documentation),
`style` (formatting only), `revert`, `test` (add or fix tests).

## Subject line (first line)

- **Length**: keep the subject to **about 50 characters**; treat that as the
  target so `git log --oneline` and UIs do not truncate it. Avoid going past
  **~72 characters** on the first line.
- **Mood**: **imperative** — write as a command (“Add handler”, “Fix race”), not
  past tense (“Added”, “Fixed”) or third person (“Adds”).
- **Capitalization**: capitalize the description (after `type:` or
  `type(scope):`).
- **Punctuation**: do not end the subject with a period.

## Body (optional, after a blank line)

- Use the body to explain **what** changed and **why** — not only how the code
  does it line by line.
- Put rationale, breaking changes, migration notes, and issue references here.
- Separate the subject from the body with **one blank line**.
- Wrap body lines at **~72 characters** where reasonable.

## Examples

Good (Conventional Commits):

```
feat(auth): Add password reset flow

Users could not recover accounts without admin help. This adds email-based
reset with expiring tokens and rate limiting on the reset endpoint.
```

Good (plain imperative, no type prefix):

```
Fix duplicate dispatch for ALL header

Registering HeaderAll no longer stores the handler under the "ALL" map key,
so Handle does not invoke the global handler twice when the message header
is literally "ALL".
```

Bad subject (vague and too long):

```
fixed stuff and also updated the tests for the dispatcher and queue
```
